# Testing Standards

## Test Pyramid

- **Unit tests** (70%): Pure functions, utilities, business logic — fast, isolated
- **Integration tests** (20%): API routes, DB queries, service interactions
- **E2E tests** (10%): Critical user journeys only — login, checkout, core workflows

## Test Structure

Use Arrange-Act-Assert (AAA) pattern with descriptive names:

```javascript
describe('CartService', () => {
  it('applies percentage discount when coupon is valid', () => {
    const cart = createCart({ items: [{ price: 100 }] });  // Arrange
    cart.applyCoupon('20OFF');                               // Act
    expect(cart.total).toBe(80);                            // Assert
  });
});
```

## Naming Convention

- `it('does X when Y')` — behavior-focused, not implementation-focused
- One assertion concept per test; multiple `expect` calls are fine if testing one behavior

## What to Test

- Business logic and state transitions
- Edge cases: empty input, boundary values, error paths, concurrent access
- API contracts (request/response shapes)
- Do NOT test framework internals, private methods, or trivial getters/setters

## Mocking

- Mock at boundaries (network, DB, file system) — not internal modules
- Prefer dependency injection over monkey-patching
- Reset mocks between tests to avoid state leakage

## CI Integration

- Tests must pass before merge — no skipping
- Track coverage trends; enforce minimum thresholds per package (e.g. 80% line coverage)
